The U.S. finally got a national bird. Government websites called bald eagles the national bird. Textbooks and newspaper articles agreed. But when Preston Cook searched high and low for any official documentation cementing the bird‚Äôs status, he found nothing. Flabbergasted, in 2011 he wrote to his senator ‚Äî the late Dianne Feinstein, a Democrat from California ‚Äî asking if her staff could investigate this mystery at the National Archives. ‚ÄúIt turns out that the documentation wasn‚Äôt missing ‚Äî it didn‚Äôt exist. We‚Äôve never had a national bird,‚Äù Cook told The Washington Post. ‚ÄúThe senator sent me back a letter saying it‚Äôs¬†assumed¬†to be our national bird, but it has never been declared our national bird.‚Äù On Monday, Congress made it official. Where did we get syphilis? In a study published Wednesday in the journal¬†Nature, an international team studied ancient DNA harvested from lesion-ridden bones or teeth of five people who lived in Peru, Chile, Argentina and Mexico either before or around the time of Columbus. They found that early versions of the microbe,¬†Treponema pallidum,¬†that causes syphilis and related diseases were already diverse and widespread. Their analysis suggests that syphilis emerged in the Americas within the last 8,000 years and spread across the globe fueled by European colonization. ‚ÄúThe syphilis debate was a big one, and it was a very emotional one ... a famous paleopathologist described it as one of the most enigmatic questions in science,‚Äù said Kirsten Bos, group leader for molecular paleopathology at the Max Planck Institute for Evolutionary Anthropology and one of the leaders of the work. She argued the new evidence would settle the matter. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs a very clear slam dunk: Okay, this clearly came from the Americas.‚Äù Several outside researchers agreed the study provides valuable new evidence strongly suggesting an American origin for syphilis, but added that it wouldn‚Äôt close the debate. Understanding the differences between the subspecies that cause these different, but related, diseases is a key question for scientists trying to understand these diseases today. Caption from article by Carolyn Y. Johnson.

FTC MAKES sellers REVEAL ‚Äújunk fees" The Federal Trade Commission on Tuesday issued long-awaited rules requiring companies to display the full price of a hotel room, concert ticket or sporting event up front to customers, rather than hiding any extra charges ‚Äî often called ‚Äújunk fees‚Äù ‚Äî until the very end of the checkout process.The new regulations, which are slated to take effect next year, seek to crack down on ‚Äúbait and switch‚Äù pricing practices, according to FTC Chair Lina Khan, who said the agency has received a groundswell of complaints about service charges, amenity fees and a raft of other potentially obscure, last-minute additions to consumers‚Äô bills. The FTC‚Äôs rules still allow companies to impose fees, so long as they are clearly displayed.The agency also focused its prohibition on just the lodging and live-event industries, not the fuller array of firms ‚Äî from airlines to internet giants ‚Äî that have similarly stoked public anger.

Young adults are far more likely to approve of Luigi Mangione. The pollster YouGov asked¬†a battery of questions¬†recently about the killing of UnitedHealthcare chief executive Brian Thompson in Manhattan two weeks ago and the man who has been charged for it, Luigi Mangione. (Mangione was¬†charged Tuesday with murder and terrorism.) Many people appeared unfamiliar with the story, offering no opinions. But among those who did, lots of young adults appeared sympathetic toward the alleged killer. And notably, they perceived those around them as sharing such views. The poll, which surveyed more than 1,000 people, showed Americans adults under 30 are about evenly split on whether they view Mangione favorably or unfavorably. About one-third hold each view. Adults aged 30 to 44 leaned only slightly negatively toward him. (In contrast, Americans aged 65-plus viewed Mangione unfavorably by about a 15-to-1 margin. Overall, Americans viewed Mangione more than 2-to-1 negatively.) Younger adults actually viewed Mangione more favorably than the man he allegedly killed, Thompson. Caption from article by Aaron Blake.

voice_to_text: in my last video I said that it was hard for me to get into Drake because he keeps bringing up random people and places that I would never give a fuck about and I got so many comments that were like ‚Äúyou're just nitpicking Drake literally every other artist does that.‚Äù and I didn't really think that was true so I did what any normal human being who's unemployed and has an infinite amount of free time would do and I listened to four albums and wrote down every single time they mentioned either a person or a place first of all this is probably gonna be a long video so I'm gonna leave a time stamp here if you just wanna skip ahead and find out if Drake really does do this more than other rappers okay so the four albums I listened to were Chromakopia GNX Donda and For All The Dogs you might be wondering why Donda instead of one of the vultures and that's just because the vultures suck and I didn't wanna listen to em I also divided every person and place into two categories ones that I recognized and were explained and ones that I didn't recognize or were redundant one last thing before we start I'm not counting repeats as long as they happen on the same song if Tyler says hey Jane 15 times that only counts once but if Drake mentions Miami one time on six different songs that's gonna count six times chromakopia has a shockingly low amount given that two songs on there are named after people I only counted 16 instances and out of those 16 only two of them were ones that I didn't recognize and they happen in the same line on Ratatata he has a line where he goes ‚Äúthem boys went to Leuzinger i skated to Hamilton.‚Äù and I had to look that up it's just about high schools in LA obviously the average person isn't gonna know that so you know two for 16 is not bad and 16 in total that's that's really low compared to the ones we're gonna get to GNX and Donda both came out to 47 most of GNX's was talking about rappers like every feature on the album said their name at least once talking about all the members of TDE the people Kendrick calls out on whacked out murals that accounted for a majority of them and then with Donda it was mostly like biblical characters and stuff like that so I knew most of them for both albums G N X ended up with three out of 47 I didn't know and then Donda it was 5 out of 47 I didn't know both pretty good ratios¬† so far we have 16 47 and 47 add those all together it's 110 I want you to guess right now whether or not you think for all the dogs had over or under 110 I'm gonna assume you know since I'm asking you that it was over Drake had 153 instances of bringing up a random person or place on that album but what's even more absurd than that is that 64 of those were ones that I didn't know and I had to Google that's absurd let's look at the percentages on this and see how crazy it is comparatively two out of the 16 times Tyler mentioned a person or place on Chromakopia¬† I didn't know what he was talking about that's 12.5% for GNX it was three out of 47 that's 6% for Donda it was five out of 47 that's 11% for for all the dogs it was 64 out of 153 that is 42% of the time Drake mentions a Person or Place I didn't know what he was talking about that's absurd obviously it's gonna be lower for the OVO goons but for a regular person not knowing what Drake's talking about 42% of the time is crazy so yeah other rappers do it but nobody does it as much as Drake does

voice_to_text: Merry Christmas get up no seriously get up it's four in the morning we have a lot of videos to make today we're gonna pretend like we're sleeping and then when you hear this phone beep three times you're gonna run in and wake us up okay you guys should be waking us up now all right you guys lots of excitement as we go downstairs to see what Santa left make it look magical no no go back go back why are you pouting now we have to redo it our kids obviously know the true meaning of Christmas but this year we decided to spoil them and we bought over 1,000 presents for them to open I know some of you guys are gonna say it‚Äôs for the clickbait¬† but it's not we actually just love our kids show me your best thumbnail face let's see it wait do not open anything you guys all right Mommy and daddy didn‚Äôt just buy all these presents so you guys can open them all Hannah Grace did Santa put pads in your stocking Hold them up so I can see them Don‚Äôt throw them Your gonna need them your becoming a woman¬† Hannah Grace threw one of her gifts because she was upset with what she got Which is not okay so ultimately we had to make the tough decision¬† To take away all of her presents which was really hard but you know parenting doesn't stop just because it's the holidays and she needs to learn to be more grateful so tomorrow daddy will be going live while he takes her to donate all of her presents to poor people I know you guys are all enjoying your presents but daddy and I have one more surprise for you look listen look at the camera You‚Äôre gonna have a new baby sister it's true we're pregnant with our 8th little So get ready for more baby bath routine videos in the future She‚Äôs gonna make us so much money

voice_to_text: what's up you guys I want you to check out this deal I'm about to talk about it's worth your time I promise you're gonna love it check it out I used to be really really identified with my anxiety it ruled all of my decisions the way I felt everything leading to me having a drinking problem now I have been doing somatic therapy dance movement therapy for the last few years dance movement therapy has been the most important part of my healing journey because learning that your brain just distracts you from what's happening in your body because when you had whatever trauma happened to you it was unsafe to feel the feelings in your body therefore the mind distracts you from what's happening in your body so getting in touch with your body and approaching it with compassion and care will help you heal so what I wanted to do was I wanted to give people affordable ways to get in touch with their body and that's where healing and body comes in so I had a meeting with Chelsea Healing and body and she really wanted to bring this to people as well they have a bunch of digestible affordable videos to get you in touch with your body to help you to start healing from anxiety depression OCD whatever they also have a get out of your mind course that you can take it's usually $222 and they are selling it right now for a hundred bucks with the code jewels J U L E s all caps they have forever changed my life and so many others with having compassion for themselves because trauma isn't our fault but it is our responsibility to heal it and as hard as that is it's so worth it
